\section{Method: The \textsc{SDAR} Paradigm}
\label{sec:method}
\textsc{SDAR} does not redesign BD; it makes BD practical on strong AR backbones via short continued training, leaving most compute to standard AR training.
Figure~\ref{fig:training} shows a schematic overview. Stage~(i) trains a standard model $\theta_{\text{AR}}$ trained with NTP objective in Eq.~\eqref{eq:ar_loss}. Stage~(ii) converts it to a BD model $\theta_{\textsc{SDAR}}$ by modifying only the \emph{attention mask} and \emph{training objective}. Inference uses BD decoding atop the $\theta_{\textsc{SDAR}}$ (\S\ref{ssec:inference}).
\subsection{Conversion Training}
\label{ssec:conversion}
\paragraph{From AR to BD}
Our recipe converts a pre-trained AR model $\theta_{\text{AR}}$ by systematically modifying both the data pipeline and the training objective.
We first corrupt the input sequence $x$ by masking a subset of tokens based on a uniformly sampled time $t$ (Eq.~\eqref{eq:forward_process_corrected}).
As visualized in Figure~\ref{fig:training}, these perturbed sequences are concatenated with their clean counterparts, governed by a hybrid attention mask that enforces inter-block causality while permitting intra-block bidirectional attention.
Under this modified setup, the model is continued-trained by switching the objective from standard NLL (Eq.~\eqref{eq:ar_loss}) to the diffusion NELBO (Eq.~\eqref{eq:blockwise_loss}).
\paragraph{Training Recipes}
We employ a two-stage training recipe: continued pre-training (CPT) followed by supervised fine-tuning (SFT).
During CPT, we further train $\theta_{\text{BD}}$ for 50B tokens, encouraging convergence to the BD paradigm.
SFT follows the same procedure, masking only response tokens while keeping prompts clean.
During SFT, we use 4B tokens to improve downstream task performance.
\section{Experimental Overview}
\label{sec:exp_overview}
We organize our empirical study into four tightly connected parts that progressively build the case for SDAR.
More details are provided in Appendix~\csadd{X}.
\paragraph{Study I: Paradigm Foundations and Training Efficiency}
We train an AR model and a MDLM \emph{from scratch}, each with 2B parameters, using the same 1T-token training data and a 4k context length.
We then run an identical 100B-token annealing phase to obtain four base variants:
AR, AR-BD (SDAR paradigm, block size 16), MDLM, and MDLM-BD.
All four models are fine-tuned with the same 4B-token SFT dataset.
This study reveals that AR provides a more compute-efficient foundation for block diffusion.
\paragraph{Study II: Scalability and Efficiency of SDAR Adaptation}
To validate the generality of our recipe, we apply the same pipeline to the Qwen3 family at 1.7B, 4B, 8B, and 30B-A3B scales, with the block size $L'=4$. Specifically, we run 50B-token (sampled from the 100B annealing dataset) CPT with a 4K length, followed by 4B-token SFT, yielding matched AR-Chat and SDAR-Chat baselines.
\paragraph{Study III: Scaling laws and usage guidelines.}
Starting from the base models ($L'=4$) from Study II, we expand the block size during SFT with $L' \in \{4, 8, 16, 32, 64\}$, and evaluate both static decoding and dynamic decoding ($\tau \in \{0.80, 0.85, 0.90, 0.95\}$).
We quantify algorithmic efficiency by effective tokens per forward pass (TPF). We additionally validate end-to-end throughput on an industrial inference engine.
\paragraph{Study IV: Scientific reasoning case study.}
Starting from the same science-aware Qwen3-30B-A3B checkpoint,
we construct an AR-Sci baseline and SDAR-Sci by training on an identical 50B-token science dataset, followed by long-CoT SFT. Both stages use a 20K context length.
This isolates the effect of the generative paradigm on scientific reasoning tasks.
\paragraph{Evaluation Settings.}
In Studies I–III, we use greedy decoding for all evaluations. In Study IV, we evaluate under both greedy decoding and sampling. For SDAR, we report static-decoding results by default; the only exception is Study III, where we additionally evaluate dynamic decoding as part of the ablation.

